Data Modelling – SCD (Slowly Changing Dimensions)


First — What Problem Does SCD Solve?

In real businesses, dimension data changes over time.

Examples:

Entity	What Changes?

Customer	city, address
Employee	department
Product	category
User	subscription plan


Now warehouse must decide:

> “Should we keep old history or overwrite it?”

That is the purpose of SCD.
---

What is a Slowly Changing Dimension?
Theory

A Slowly Changing Dimension (SCD) is a technique used in data warehouses to manage changes in dimension data over time.

Dimension attributes do not remain static forever.

They evolve slowly.

---

Real Example

At Amazon
Customer Ravi:
customer_id	name	city

C101	Ravi	Mumbai


Later Ravi moves to Bangalore.

Now warehouse must decide:

Option 1

Overwrite Mumbai
OR

Option 2

Keep both Mumbai and Bangalore history

Different businesses need different behavior.
---

Types of SCD
Main ones:
Type	Behavior
Type 1	Overwrite old data
Type 2	Keep full history
Type 3	Keep limited previous value

---

SCD Type 1 ⭐

Theory

In SCD Type 1:

> Old value is overwritten with new value.
No history preserved.

---

Example

Before Update

customer_id	name	city

C101	Ravi	Mumbai

---

After Update
Ravi moves to Bangalore.
customer_id	name	city
C101	Ravi	Bangalore
Mumbai history gone.

---

Important Point
Only latest/current value exists.
Warehouse does NOT remember old value.
---
Why Use SCD Type 1?
Used when:
historical tracking not important
incorrect data needs correction
only latest state matters
---

Real Use Cases
Example 1 — Spelling Correction
Wrong:
“Bangalre”
Correct:
“Bangalore”
No need history.
---

Example 2 — Customer Phone Number
Business only needs latest phone number.
---

Example 3 — Typo Fixes
Name correction.
---
SQL Style Update Logic
UPDATE dim_customer
SET city = 'Bangalore'
WHERE customer_id = 'C101';
Simple overwrite.
---

Advantages of SCD Type 1 ⭐
1. Simple Design

Easy ETL logic.
---

2. Less Storage

Only current row maintained.
---

3. Fast Queries

No multiple historical records.
---

Disadvantages ⚠️

1. History Lost
Cannot answer:
> “Where did customer live last year?”
Impossible.
---

2. Historical Reports Become Incorrect

Past reports may change unexpectedly.
---

Important Interview Insight ⭐

SCD Type 1 is NOT suitable when business needs historical analysis.

This is critical.
---

Example Problem

Suppose:
2024: Ravi in Mumbai
2025: Ravi in Bangalore

If overwritten:
Old sales reports now incorrectly show Bangalore for past orders too.
History corrupted.
---

Where SCD Type 1 Commonly Used

Used for:
typo corrections
non-historical attributes
low-value attributes
latest-state systems
---

Comparison So Far
Feature	SCD Type 1

History Preserved	No
Overwrite Data	Yes
Storage	Small
Complexity	Low
---

Common Interview Questions

Q1. What is SCD Type 1?
Overwrites old dimension data with new value without preserving history.
---

Q2. When should Type 1 be used?
When historical tracking is unnecessary.
---
Q3. Main disadvantage?
Loss of historical information.
---


Real Industry Insight ⭐

Many warehouses use:

Type 1 for low-value attributes

Type 2 for business-critical historical attributes


Combination approach.


---

# SCD Type 1

## Definition
Overwrites old dimension data with new value.

## History
Not preserved.

## Example
Mumbai -> Bangalore
Old value replaced.

## Advantages
- Simple
- Less storage
- Fast queries

## Disadvantages
- History lost
- Past reports may become incorrect

## Use Cases
- Typo correction
- Latest state only
- Non-historical attributes

